---
import ExternalLink from "../../components/ExternalLink.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Policy and Standards"
  seoTitle="Editorial Policy | Australian Home Collective"
  description="How Australian Home Collective develops, reviews and corrects independent home-planning and buying guidance for Australian households."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">How we publish</p>
      <h1>Editorial Policy and Standards</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        These commitments explain how we develop practical guidance, protect editorial
        independence and take responsibility for what we publish.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <h2>Our approach</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective exists to help Australians make informed home-planning and
      buying decisions before they spend money.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our guides focus on practical considerations such as measurements, planning,
      compatibility, delivery, installation, ownership and long-term suitability. Rather than
      telling readers what to buy, we explain what to consider so they can choose products that
      suit their homes, circumstances and budgets.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial independence</h2>
    <p>
      Editorial decisions are made independently. Commercial relationships, affiliate
      partnerships and advertising opportunities do not determine the topics we cover or the
      conclusions we reach.
    </p>
    <p>
      If a product, category or approach may not suit a particular situation, we will say so,
      even when that means suggesting readers delay a purchase or consider another approach.
      Maintaining reader trust is more important than maximising short-term revenue.
    </p>

    <h2>How we develop guides</h2>
    <p>
      Our articles draw on practical planning principles, published specifications,
      authoritative guidance where appropriate and common buying considerations relevant to
      Australian households.
    </p>
    <p>Many guides focus on details that are easy to overlook, including:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>measurements and clearances</li>
      <li>delivery access</li>
      <li>installation requirements</li>
      <li>room layout and compatibility</li>
      <li>maintenance and service access</li>
      <li>after-sales support considerations</li>
      <li>long-term usability</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Where requirements vary between products, manufacturers, installers or homes, we explain
      that variation rather than presenting one answer as universal.
    </p>

    <h2>Publication edit before publishing</h2>
    <p>
      Every new guide and every substantial update receives a publication edit after the facts
      and structure are in place. This separate pass should:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>remove repeated ideas and formulaic wording</li>
      <li>improve the rhythm and transitions between sections</li>
      <li>use specific household observations instead of generic filler</li>
      <li>vary headings and section patterns where the subject allows</li>
      <li>apply Australian English and consistent terminology</li>
      <li>preserve factual accuracy, search intent and useful links</li>
      <li>keep safety cautions, disclosures and commercial boundaries intact</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The aim is publication-quality copy that sounds considered and natural, not wording
      designed to influence automated detection tools.
    </p>

    <h2>Accuracy, sources and editorial responsibility</h2>
    <p>
      We make every reasonable effort to publish accurate, clear and current information. Every
      article is reviewed before publication, and Australian Home Collective accepts
      responsibility for the content it publishes.
    </p>
    <p>
      We prefer primary, current and authoritative sources for factual, legal, safety and
      product-specific information. These may include Australian government agencies,
      recognised authorities and manufacturer documentation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Products, specifications, standards and manufacturer requirements can change. Readers
      should confirm critical measurements, current specifications and installation
      requirements before buying or installing a product.
    </p>

    <h2>Product guidance and claims</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective is not a product-testing laboratory unless a specific article
      clearly states what testing was performed. We do not claim to have tested, owned or
      inspected a product when we have not.
    </p>
    <p>Our usual role is to help readers understand:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>what to measure and compare</li>
      <li>what questions to ask</li>
      <li>which features matter in different circumstances</li>
      <li>what ownership and support considerations may apply</li>
      <li>which common mistakes can be avoided before purchase</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Different homes, budgets and priorities can lead to different reasonable choices. We
      avoid unsupported best-product claims and claims that one product is right for every
      household.
    </p>

    <h2>Commercial relationships and sponsored content</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective may participate in affiliate or referral programs. If a reader
      purchases through a qualifying link, Australian Home Collective may receive a commission.
      These commissions help fund the publication, but they do not determine our editorial
      standards or conclusions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Material commercial relationships will be disclosed clearly. If sponsored content is
      accepted, it will be identified and will still be required to meet our editorial
      standards. Sponsored material will not be presented as independent editorial without
      appropriate disclosure. Read our <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/">Affiliate Disclosure</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Interactive planning tools</h2>
    <p>
      Our planning tools assist with planning and decision-making. They do not replace current
      manufacturer information, a site-specific assessment, delivery-provider requirements,
      qualified tradespeople or professional advice where required.
    </p>
    <p>
      Results depend on the information entered and the assumptions explained within each tool.
      Users should independently verify important measurements and requirements before
      purchasing, delivering or installing a product.
    </p>

    <h2>Consumer information</h2>
    <p>
      Where relevant, we may explain in general terms that automatic consumer guarantees under
      Australian Consumer Law are separate from voluntary warranties. We do not provide legal
      advice or interpret individual disputes.
    </p>
    <p>
      For authoritative information, refer to the ACCC's
      <ExternalLink href="https://www.accc.gov.au/consumers/buying-products-and-services/consumer-rights-and-guarantees">
        consumer rights and guarantees guidance
      </ExternalLink>.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections and feedback</h2>
    <p>
      We welcome reports of inaccurate, outdated or unclear information. Every substantive
      report will be reviewed, and appropriate corrections or clarifications will be made.
      Read our <a href="/corrections-content-review-policy/">Corrections &amp; Content Review Policy</a>
      or use the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> to report an issue.
    </p>

    <h2>Our commitment</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective is committed to practical, trustworthy and independent
      guidance that helps Australians make better decisions for their homes.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Every article has one objective: help readers avoid expensive mistakes before they happen.</strong></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
